## 2 Background and model setup

We use the subscript \({}_{\rm t}\) to indicate the true parameters. For a \(p\)-dimensional vector \(\bm{x}\), we use \(x_{(i)}\) to represent its \(i\)-th element. For an index subset \(\mathcal{A}\subset\{i:1,2,...,p\}\), we use \(\bm{x}_{(\mathcal{A})}\) to denote the subvector of \(\bm{x}\), whose elements correspond to the indexes in \(\mathcal{A}\). Furthermore, we use \(\bm{x}^{\otimes 2}\) to denote \(\bm{x}\bm{x}^{\rm T}\), use "\(\bm{\sim}\)" to denote convergence in distribution, use "\(\bm{\sim}\)" to denote convergence in probability, and use "\(\bm{\sim}\)" to denote convergence almost surely. We use \(\bm{I}\) to denote an identity matrix of a suitable dimension and use \(\bm{0}\) to denote a vector of zeros of a suitable dimension.

Let \((\bm{x}_{1},y_{1}),(\bm{x}_{2},y_{2}),...,(\bm{x}_{N},y_{N})\) denote \(N\) sample points from the joint distribution of \((\bm{x},y)\), where \(\{\bm{x}_{i}\}_{i=1}^{N}\) denote the \(p\)-dimensional predictors and \(\{y_{i}\}_{i=1}^{N}\) the binary responses. Assume that the probability of \(y\) being a one (\(y=1\)) given \(\bm{x}\) is

\[p(\bm{x};\bm{\theta}_{\rm t}):=\mathbb{P}(y=1|\bm{x})=\frac{e^{\alpha_{\rm t}+ f(\bm{x};\bm{\beta}_{\rm t})}}{1+e^{\alpha_{\rm t}+f(\bm{x};\bm{\beta}_{\rm t})}}= \frac{e^{g(\bm{x};\bm{\theta}_{\rm t})}}{1+e^{g(\bm{x};\bm{\theta}_{\rm t})}},\]

where \(\bm{\theta}_{\rm t}=(\alpha_{\rm t},\bm{\beta}_{\rm t}^{\rm T})^{\rm T}\) is the vector of true parameters and \(f(\bm{x};\bm{\beta}_{\rm t})\) is a smooth function of \(\bm{\beta}_{t}\). For rare-events data, \(N_{1}\ll N_{0}\), where \(N_{1}=\sum_{i=1}^{N}y_{i}\) is the number of ones (i.e. \(y_{i}=1\)) and \(N_{0}=N-N_{1}\) is the number of zeros (i.e. \(y_{i}=0\)). Following the model setup used in [22], we assume that \(\alpha_{\rm t}\rightarrow-\infty\) as \(N\rightarrow\infty\), which implies that, under appropriate moment conditions,

\[\frac{N_{1}}{N_{0}}=\frac{\mathbb{E}\{p(\bm{x};\bm{\theta}_{\rm t})\}}{1- \mathbb{E}\{p(\bm{x};\bm{\theta}_{\rm t})\}}+o(1)=\mathbb{E}\{e^{\alpha_{\rm t }+f(\bm{x};\bm{\beta}_{\rm t})}\}+o(1)\to 0,\ \text{almost surely}.\] (1)

Under this assumption, the asymptotic variance of the full data maximum likelihood estimator (MLE) is of order \(1/N_{1}\) instead of \(1/N\), indicating that the estimation efficiency is determined by the number of rare ones. Therefore, we can keep all the ones and sample the zeros to save computational costs. There could be a variance inflation due to aggressive subsampling, and [22] developed optimal subsampling functions to reduce the variance inflation. Specifically, the authors proposed non-uniform optimal sampling functions under the A- and L-optimality criteria, respectively, as follows: \(\varphi^{\rm scale}_{\rm A-OS}(\bm{x})\propto p(\bm{x};\bm{\theta}_{\rm t})\| \bm{M}^{-1}\hat{g}(\bm{x};\bm{\theta}_{\rm t})\|\) and \(\varphi^{\rm scale}_{\rm L-OS}(\bm{x})\propto p(\bm{x};\bm{\theta}_{\rm t})\| \hat{g}(\bm{x};\bm{\theta}_{\rm t})\|\), where \(\bm{M}=\mathbb{E}\{e^{f(\bm{x};\bm{\beta}_{\rm t})}\hat{g}^{\otimes 2}(\bm{x};\bm{ \theta}_{\rm t})\}\) and \(\hat{g}(\bm{x};\bm{\theta})\) denotes the derivative of \(g(\bm{x};\bm{\theta})\) with respect to \(\bm{\theta}\). However, the sampling functions \(\varphi^{\rm scale}_{\rm A-OS}(\bm{x})\) and \(\varphi^{\rm scale}_{\rm L-OS}(\bm{x})\) proposed in [22] depend on the scale of \(\bm{x}\), and may not perform well for certain measurement scale of \(\bm{x}\). For example, if \(g(\bm{x};\bm{\theta}_{\rm t})=\alpha_{\rm t}+\bm{x}^{\rm T}\bm{\theta}_{\rm t}\), then \(\varphi^{\rm scale}_{\rm L-OS}(\bm{x})\) is proportional to \(1+\|\bm{x}\|\), which will be influenced by the scale of \(\bm{x}\). Similarly, scale changes in \(\bm{x}\) may also change \(\varphi^{\rm scale}_{\rm A-OS}(\bm{x})\), although the impact may not be in the same direction, as demonstrated in Figure 1. Besides parameter estimation, variable selection is another important topic, which has not been studied in the literature on rare-events data. This work aims to fill this gap.

## 3 Nonuniform sampling with variable selection for rare-events data

The adaptive lasso [30; 28] is a popular variable selection method because it has oracle properties and is easy to implement. We define the full data adaptive lasso for rare-events data as

\[\hat{\bm{\theta}}^{\rm adp}_{\rm mle}:=\arg\max_{\bm{\theta}}\left\{\sum_{i=1 }^{N}[y_{i}g(\bm{x}_{i};\bm{\theta})-\log\{1+e^{g(\bm{x}_{i};\bm{\theta})}\}] -\lambda_{N}\sum_{j=1}^{p}\frac{|\beta_{(j)}|}{|\hat{\beta}_{\rm pl(j)}|^{ \gamma}}\right\},\] (2)

where \(\lambda_{N}\) and \(\gamma\) are tuning parameters, and \(\hat{\bm{\beta}}_{\rm pl}\) is a consistent pilot estimator of \(\bm{\beta}_{t}\). In practice, it is common to set \(\gamma=1\). In the literature, iterative algorithms such as coordinate descent are commonly used to solve the adaptive lasso [8]. However, their computational demand can become prohibitive when dealing with massive data. It is feasible to alleviate the computational burden by subsampling zeros and create a smaller subset of data for adaptive lasso. To be specific, consider Algorithm 1.

```
1:For \(i=1,...,N\):
2:if\(y_{i}=1\)then
3: include \((\bm{x}_{i},y_{i})\) in the subsample;
4:else
5: Compute \(\varphi(\bm{x}_{i})\) and generate \(u_{i}\sim U[0,1]\);
6:if\(u_{i}\leq\pi(\bm{x}_{i},y_{i})\)then
7: include \((\bm{x}_{i},y_{i})\) and record \(\rho\varphi(\bm{x}_{i})\) in the subsample;
8:endif ```

**Algorithm 1** Poisson Subsampling algorithm

The inclusion probability in Algorithm 1 for the \(i\)th observation is \(\pi(\bm{x}_{i},y_{i})=y_{i}+(1-y_{i})\rho\varphi(\bm{x}_{i})\), where \(\rho\) is the baseline sampling rate for the zeros and \(\varphi(\bm{x})>0\) satisfies \(\mathbb{E}\{\varphi(\bm{x})\}=1\). Let the subsample from Algorithm 1 be \(\{\bm{x}_{i}^{\rm sub},y_{i}^{\rm sub}\}_{i=1}^{N_{\rm sub}^{*}}\), which is biased since \(\pi(\bm{x}_{i},y_{i})\)'s depend on the responses. We introduce an Inverse Probability Weighting (IPW) adaptive lasso estimator to correct for the bias, defined as

\[\hat{\bm{\theta}}^{\rm adp}_{\rm w}:=\arg\max_{\bm{\theta}}\left\{\sum_{i=1}^{ N_{\rm sub}^{*}}\frac{[y_{i}^{\rm sub}g(\bm{x}_{i}^{\rm sub};\bm{\theta})- \log\{1+e^{g(\bm{x}_{i}^{\rm sub};\bm{\theta})}\}]}{\pi(\bm{x}_{i}^{\rm sub},y_ {i}^{\rm sub})}-\lambda_{N}\sum_{j=1}^{p}\frac{|\beta_{(j)}|}{|\hat{\beta}_{\rm pl (j)}|^{\gamma}}\right\}.\] (3)

