From Theorem 1, we see that there maybe information loss reflected as an inflated variance if \(c\neq 0\). To minimize the information loss due to sampling, we derive optimal functions as follows, where \(\varphi^{\mathrm{adp}}_{\mathrm{A-OS}}(\bm{x})\) corresponds to the A-optimality criterion [17] and \(\varphi^{\mathrm{adp}}_{\mathrm{L-OS}}(\bm{x})\) corresponds to the L-optimality criterion [17] in design of experiments. Here, the A-optimality minimizes the trace of the asymptotic variance of \(\hat{\bm{\theta}}^{\mathrm{adp}}_{\mathrm{w}(\mathcal{A})}\); the L-optimality focuses on the asymptotic variance of a linearly transformed estimator \(\bm{M}_{(\mathcal{A})}\hat{\bm{\theta}}^{\mathrm{adp}}_{\mathrm{w}(\mathcal{ A})}\), which is proportional to \(\bm{M}_{\mathrm{w}(\mathcal{A})}\). The A-optimality criterion has a more direct interpretation, while an advantage of the L-optimality criterion is that the resulting optimal function is often faster to calculate.

**Proposition 1**.: _The A-optimal function that minimizes \(\text{tr}(\bm{V}_{\mathrm{w}(\mathcal{A})})\) is_

\[\varphi^{\mathrm{adp}}_{\mathrm{A-OS}}(\bm{x})=\frac{p(\bm{x};\bm{\theta}_{ \mathrm{t}})\|\bm{M}_{(\mathcal{A})}^{-1}\hat{g}_{(\mathcal{A})}(\bm{x};\bm{ \theta}_{\mathrm{t}})\|}{\mathbb{E}\left\{p(\bm{x};\bm{\theta}_{\mathrm{t}}) \|\bm{M}_{(\mathcal{A})}^{-1}\hat{g}_{(\mathcal{A})}(\bm{x};\bm{\theta}_{ \mathrm{t}})\right\}}.\] (4)

_The L-optimal function that minimizes \(\text{tr}(\bm{M}_{\mathrm{w}(\mathcal{A})})\) is_

\[\varphi^{\mathrm{adp}}_{\mathrm{L-OS}}(\bm{x})=\frac{p(\bm{x};\bm{\theta}_{ \mathrm{t}})\|\hat{g}_{(\mathcal{A})}(\bm{x};\bm{\theta}_{\mathrm{t}})\|}{ \mathbb{E}\left\{p(\bm{x};\bm{\theta}_{\mathrm{t}})\|\hat{g}_{(\mathcal{A})} (\bm{x};\bm{\theta}_{\mathrm{t}})\right\}}.\] (5)

Unlike the optimal sampling function in [22], \(\varphi^{\mathrm{adp}}_{\mathrm{A-OS}}(\bm{x})\) (or \(\varphi^{\mathrm{adp}}_{\mathrm{L-OS}}(\bm{x})\)) relies only on the active variables. This implies that a first-step pilot estimator given by the adaptive lasso algorithm can benefit from sparse estimation methods when calculating optimal probabilities. For example, employing the standard lasso can effectively eliminate a large number of inactive variables to facilitate the computation of optimal \(\varphi^{\mathrm{adp}}_{\mathrm{A-OS}}(\bm{x})\) and \(\varphi^{\mathrm{adp}}_{\mathrm{L-OS}}(\bm{x})\). However, in practice, pilot estimators are often obtained from a small subsample size, introducing additional uncertainty. Therefore, it becomes crucial to exercise caution and be conservative by over-selecting variables during the first step to prevent the exclusion of important variables. As a consequence, although theoretically \(\varphi^{\mathrm{adp}}_{\mathrm{A-OS}}(\bm{x})\) and \(\varphi^{\mathrm{adp}}_{\mathrm{L-OS}}(\bm{x})\) do not depend on inactive variables, they are affected by inactive variables in practical implementations.

### Scale invariant optimal function

As discussed in Section 1, scaling dependent optimal probabilities may impact the performance of variable selection in practice. To address the issue, we propose to construct a scale invariant optimal function by focusing on the prediction error of an estimator \(\hat{\bm{\theta}}\), defined below.

\[\mathrm{MSPE}(\hat{\bm{\theta}})=\mathbb{E}_{\bm{x}}\left[\left\{p(\bm{x};\hat {\bm{\theta}})-p(\bm{x};\bm{\theta}_{\mathrm{t}})\right\}^{2}\right]=\int \left\{p(\bm{x};\hat{\bm{\theta}})-p(\bm{x};\bm{\theta}_{\mathrm{t}})\right\}^ {2}\mathrm{d}\mathbb{P}_{\bm{x}},\]

where \(\mathbb{P}_{\bm{x}}\) is the probability measure of \(\bm{x}\). The probability term \(p(\bm{x};\bm{\theta}_{\mathrm{t}})\) involves both the covariates \(\bm{x}\) and the parameter vector \(\bm{\theta}_{\mathrm{t}}\), and it often does not depend on the scale of \(\bm{x}\). For example, in the logistic regression model, the value \(p(\bm{x};\bm{\theta}_{\mathrm{t}})\) is only related to \(\bm{x}^{\mathrm{T}}\bm{\beta}_{\mathrm{t}}\). If we change the scale of \(x_{(j)}\), the value of \(\bm{\theta}_{\mathrm{t}}\) would change accordingly under the same data-generating model and so \(p(\bm{x};\bm{\theta}_{\mathrm{t}})\) remains the same. Thus, re-scaling covariates would not affect this criterion. In the following, we give an optimal function that minimizes the prediction error.

**Theorem 2**.: _Under the assumptions of Theorem 1, for the IPW adaptive lasso estimator defined in (3), its prediction error satisfies_

\[N_{1}e^{-2\alpha_{\mathrm{t}}}\mathrm{MSPE}(\hat{\bm{\theta}}^{\mathrm{adp}}_{ \mathrm{w}(\mathcal{A})})\rightsquigarrow\mathbb{E}^{-1}\left\{e^{f(\bm{x}; \bm{\beta}_{\mathrm{t}})}\right\}\bm{Z}^{\mathrm{T}}_{(\mathcal{A})}\bm{M}^{1/ 2}_{\mathrm{w}(\mathcal{A})}\bm{M}^{-1}_{(\mathcal{A})}\bm{\Omega}_{(\mathcal{A} )}\bm{M}^{-1}_{(\mathcal{A})}\bm{M}^{1/2}_{\mathrm{w}(\mathcal{A})}\bm{Z}_{( \mathcal{A})}.\] (6)_where \(\bm{Z}_{(\mathcal{A})}\sim\mathbb{N}(\bm{0},\bm{I})\), and \(\bm{\Omega}_{(\mathcal{A})}=\mathbb{E}\left[e^{2f(\bm{x};\bm{\theta}_{1})}\dot{y }_{(\mathcal{A})}^{\otimes 2}(\bm{x},\bm{\theta}_{1})\right]\). The optimal function that minimizes the asymptotic mean of the prediction error in (6) is given as_

\[\varphi_{\mathrm{P-OS}}^{\mathrm{adp}}(\bm{x})=\frac{p(\bm{x};\bm{\theta}_{1}) \|\bm{\Omega}_{(\mathcal{A})}^{\frac{1}{2}}\bm{M}_{(\mathcal{A})}^{-1}\dot{y }_{(\mathcal{A})}(\bm{x};\bm{\theta}_{1})\|}{\mathbb{E}\left[p(\bm{x};\bm{ \theta}_{1})\|\bm{\Omega}_{(\mathcal{A})}^{\frac{1}{2}}\bm{M}_{(\mathcal{A}) }^{-1}\dot{y}_{(\mathcal{A})}(\bm{x};\bm{\theta}_{1})\|\right]}.\] (7)

We refer this prediction oriented criterion as P-optimality criterion. As we expect, the optimal function in (7) is unaffected by the scale of \(\bm{x}\) for a class of functions \(g\). The following proposition proves that \(\varphi_{\mathrm{P-OS}}^{\mathrm{adp}}(\bm{x})\) is invariant to rescaling of \(\bm{x}\).

**Proposition 2**.: _If \(g(\bm{x};\bm{\theta})\) satisfies that for every non-singular matrix \(\bm{A}\) there exists a non-singular matrix \(\bm{B}\), such that_

\[g(\bm{A}\bm{x};\bm{B}^{\mathrm{T}}\bm{\theta})=g(\bm{x};\bm{\theta}),\] (8)

_then, \(\varphi_{\mathrm{P-OS}}^{\mathrm{adp}}(\bm{x})\) is invariant to scale changes of \(\bm{x}\)._

**Remark 2**.: _The condition in (8) is not restrictive and it is quite easy to satisfy. One simple example of \(g(\bm{x};\bm{\theta})\) that satisfies the condition is a linear function \(g(\bm{x};\bm{\theta})=\alpha+\bm{x}^{\mathrm{T}}\bm{\beta}\), which corresponds to the logistic regression. The condition is also satisfied by more complex models. For example, consider an L-layer neural network_

\[g(\bm{x};\bm{W}^{1},\bm{W}^{2},...,\bm{W}^{L},\bm{b}^{1},...,\bm{b}^{L})=f^{L} (f^{L-1}(...f^{1}(\bm{x}^{\mathrm{T}}\bm{W}^{1}+\bm{b}^{1}))^{\mathrm{T}}\bm{ W}+\bm{b}^{L}),\]

_where \(\bm{W}^{l}\) are the weights and \(\bm{b}^{l}\) are the biases in each layer, \(l=1,2,...,L\). If \(\bm{x}\) is rescaled to \(\bm{A}\bm{x}\), we can change \(\bm{W}^{1}\) to \((\bm{A}^{T})^{-1}\bm{W}^{1}\) so that the value of \(g\) does not change. That is_

\[g(\bm{A}\bm{x};(\bm{A}^{T})^{-1}\bm{W}^{1},\bm{W}^{2},...,\bm{W}^ {L},\bm{b}^{1},...,\bm{b}^{L})=f^{L}(f^{L-1}(...f^{1}(\bm{x}^{\mathrm{T}}\bm{ W}^{1}+\bm{b}^{1}))^{\mathrm{T}}\bm{W}+\bm{b}^{L})\] \[=g(\bm{x};\bm{W}^{1},\bm{W}^{2},...,\bm{W}^{L},\bm{b}^{1},...,\bm {b}^{L}).\]

## 4 Penalized MSCL estimator

The IPW estimator in (3) is not the most efficient estimator, because it assigns smaller weights for more informative data points with larger sampling probabilities. To improve the estimation efficiency, we propose the penalized MSCL estimator for variable selection given as

\[\hat{\bm{\theta}}_{\mathrm{mscl}}^{\mathrm{adp}}:=\operatorname*{arg\,max}_{ \bm{\theta}}\left\{\sum_{i=1}^{N_{\mathrm{null}}^{\mathrm{sub}}}[y_{i}^{ \mathrm{sub}}g(\bm{x}_{i}^{\mathrm{sub}};\bm{\theta})-\log\{1+e^{g(\bm{x}_{i}^{ \mathrm{sub}},\bm{\theta})+l_{i}^{\mathrm{sub}}}\}]-\lambda_{N}\sum_{j=1}^{p} \frac{|\beta_{(j)}|}{|\hat{\beta}_{\mathrm{pl}(j)}|^{\gamma}}\right\},\] (9)

where \(l_{i}^{\mathrm{sub}}=-\log\left\{\rho\varphi(\bm{x}_{i}^{\mathrm{sub}})\right\}\). The MSCL estimator introduced in [22] is defined as the minimizer of the objective function in (9), excluding the penalization term. In this paper, we extend this approach by proposing a penalized MSCL estimator to ensure model sparsity. We present the oracle properties of the penalized MSCL estimator in the following theorem.

**Theorem 3**.: _Let \(\hat{\bm{\beta}}_{\mathrm{pl}}\) be a consistent pilot estimate such that \(\lambda_{N}/(\sqrt{N_{1}}|\hat{\beta}_{\mathrm{pl}(j)}|^{\gamma})\overset{P} {\longrightarrow}\infty\) for \(j\in\mathcal{A}^{c}\). Under Assumptions 1-3 and 5, if \(\lambda_{N}/\sqrt{N_{1}}\to 0\), the estimator based on MSCL function with adaptive lasso penalty defined in (9) have the following properties:_

1. _Consistency in variable selection: The estimated active set_ \(\hat{\mathcal{A}}_{\mathrm{mscl}}:=\{j:\hat{\beta}_{\mathrm{mscl}(j)}^{\mathrm{ adp}}\neq 0\}\) _satisfies that_ \(\lim_{N\to\infty}\mathbb{P}(\hat{\mathcal{A}}_{\mathrm{mscl}}=\mathcal{A})=1\)__
2. _Asymptotic normality: The estimator of the active parameter vector satisfies that_ \[\sqrt{N_{1}}\bm{V}_{\mathrm{mscl}(\mathcal{A})}^{-1/2}(\hat{\bm{\theta}}_{ \mathrm{mscl}(\mathcal{A})}^{\mathrm{adp}}-\bm{\theta}_{\mathrm{t}(\mathcal{A})} )\rightsquigarrow\mathbb{N}(\bm{0},\bm{I}),\] (10) _where_ \(\bm{V}_{\mathrm{mscl}(\mathcal{A})}=\mathbb{E}\left\{e^{f(\bm{x};\bm{\beta}_{i}) }\right\}\bm{\Lambda}_{\mathrm{mscl}(\mathcal{A})}^{-1}\) _and_ \(\bm{\Lambda}_{\mathrm{mscl}(\mathcal{A})}=\mathbb{E}\left[\frac{e^{f(\bm{x};\bm{ \beta}_{i})}\hat{\beta}_{(\mathcal{A})}^{\otimes 2}(\bm{x};\bm{\beta}_{i})}{1+c\varphi^{-1}(\bm{x})e^{f(\bm{x};\bm{ \beta}_{i})}}\right]\)_._

The penalized MSCL estimator has the same asymptotic variance as the MSCL estimator under the true model, indicating that it is more efficient than the penalized IPW estimator [22]. We prove this by comparing the asymptotic variances and present the result in the following theorem.

**Theorem 4**.: _If the asymptotic variances \(\bm{V}_{\mathrm{w}(\mathcal{A})}\) for \(\hat{\bm{\theta}}_{\mathrm{w}(\mathcal{A})}^{\mathrm{adp}}\) in (2) and \(\bm{V}_{\mathrm{mscl}(\mathcal{A})}\) for \(\hat{\bm{\theta}}_{\mathrm{mscl}(\mathcal{A})}^{\mathrm{adp}}\) in (9), are finite, i.e., \(0<\bm{V}_{\mathrm{w}(\mathcal{A})},\bm{V}_{\mathrm{mscl}(\mathcal{A})}<\infty\), then \(\bm{V}_{\mathrm{mscl}(\mathcal{A})}\leq\bm{V}_{\mathrm{w}(\mathcal{A})}\), where the inequalities hold in the sense of Loewner ordering._

Thus, we give a practical two-step algorithm based on the penalized MSCL estimator. Since the optimal sampling functions contain unknown values and the adaptive lasso penalty also requires a consistent pilot estimator to build weights, it is natural to combine optimal sampling and the adaptive lasso into one unified framework. We recommend to use the lasso for pilot estimation. One reason is that it does estimation and variable selection simultaneously, and excluding some inactive variables improves the estimation accuracy of optimal probabilities. This also reduces the computational burden for subsequent steps. Another reason is that the lasso estimator tends to include more variables in practice and therefore has a low risk of excluding important variables in the pilot step. We present an outline of the practical implementation in Algorithm 2. More details are given in Section C.

```
1: First stage screening: * Take a pilot sample of expected sample size \(N_{\mathrm{pl}}\) using \(\{\pi(y_{i})=\rho_{0}+y_{i}(\rho_{1}-\rho_{0})\}_{i=1}^{N}\) and obtain a lasso penalized MSCL pilot estimator and an estimated active set \(\hat{\mathcal{A}}_{\mathrm{pl}}\). * Calculate approximate optimal sampling probabilities \(\{\hat{\pi}(\bm{x}_{i},y_{i})=y_{i}+(1-y_{i})\rho\hat{\varphi}(x_{i})\}_{i=1}^ {N}\) based on (4), (5), or (7).
2: Second stage screening: Use Algorithm 1 with the estimated optimal sampling probabilities to obtain a subsample of expected sample size \(N_{\mathrm{sub}}\) and compute the adaptive lasso penalized MSCL estimator based on \(\hat{\mathcal{A}}_{\mathrm{pl}}\). ```

