### Simulation in Section 1

We first present the detailed settings of the simulations in Section 1, where we illustrate the scale-dependent issues of optimal subsampling probabilities. Our simulation based on logistic regression models with the true parameter \(\bm{\beta}_{\mathrm{t}}\) to be 6-dimentional vectors and covariates \(\bm{x}\sim lognormal(\bm{0},\bm{\Sigma})\) with the \((i,j)\)-th element of \(\bm{\Sigma}\) is given as \(\bm{\Sigma}_{ij}=0.5^{|i-j|},1\leq i,j\leq 6\). We consider two cases of parameters:

1. **Non-sparse parameter**: \(\bm{\beta}_{\mathrm{t}}=(-1,-1,-0.01,-0.01,-0.01)\) and \(\alpha_{\mathrm{t}}=-4\).
2. **Sparse parameter**: \(\bm{\beta}_{\mathrm{t}}=(-1,0,0,0,0,0)\) and \(\alpha_{\mathrm{t}}=-5\).

We generate full data of size \(N=500000\) according to the above logistic models. To investigate the effects of scale transformation, we multiply the \(\bm{x}_{(6)}\) with \(s\) (\(s=0.01,0.1,1,10,100\)) and divide \(\bm{\beta}_{\mathrm{t}(6)}\) with the same \(s\) to remain \(\bm{x}^{\mathrm{T}}\bm{\beta}_{\mathrm{t}}\) to be the same and thus the logistics regression model does not change. We obtain subsamples with optimal subsampling probabilities described in [22] with transformed \(\bm{x}\) under each \(s\) and calculate the resultant subsampling estimators. We set the nominal pilot sample size to \(N_{\mathrm{pl}}=800\) and nominal subsample size \(N_{\mathrm{sub}}=1000\) (see details in [22]). We repeat the experiment for 500 times under each scale and compute the mean prediction error.

### Simulations in Section 5

For the estimation procedures in the second step of our two-step algorithm, we choose \(\gamma=1\), which means that the weights in the adaptive lasso penalty are \(\hat{w}_{j}=1/|\hat{\beta}_{\mathrm{pl}(j)}|,1\leq j\leq q\), with \(q\) being the number of selected variables in the first stage screening. Furthermore, we consider uniform sampling, the full data lasso and the full data adaptive lasso as baselines for comparison. For the uniform sampling method, we use a similar two-step algorithm as presented in Algorithm 2 but set the sampling function in the second step as \(\varphi(\bm{x})=1\), which means the sampling probabilities are a constant \(\rho\). We use lasso to implement the first stage screening and adaptive lasso with \(\gamma=1\) to implement the second stage screening for a fair comparison. For full data lasso, we directly apply the lasso algorithm to the full data. For the full data adaptive lasso, we use the full data MLE estimator as the pilot estimator to construct the weights and then apply the adaptive lasso algorithm to the full data set.

